---
name: cross-platform-bash-xcode
description: "iOS-specific: Xcode developer dir detection via xcode-select. Required on macOS for xcodebuild commands. Cross-platform check protects against running iOS runner on Linux/Windows."
metadata:
  node_type: memory
  type: feedback
---

For iOS work, the build toolchain is **Xcode** (macOS only). Set `DEVELOPER_DIR` from `xcode-select -p` so `xcodebuild`, `simctl`, and friends find the right SDK.

**Why:** `DEVELOPER_DIR` overrides the default Xcode location. Without it, `xcodebuild` uses whatever `xcode-select` points to — which is usually fine, but multiple Xcode installs (beta + stable) can cause subtle issues. Explicit `DEVELOPER_DIR` makes the toolchain deterministic.

**Also why:** If you're running `{{PREFIX}}-runner-ios` from a Linux or Windows machine (e.g. via SSH or remote dev), `xcode-select` won't exist — the runner should fail loudly, not silently use a wrong toolchain.

**How to apply:**

The detection block is in `{{PREFIX}}-runner-ios` agent and as a standalone snippet at `templates/ios/snippets/xcode-detect.sh`:

```bash
if command -v xcode-select >/dev/null 2>&1; then
    if dir=$(xcode-select -p 2>/dev/null) && [ -n "$dir" ]; then
        export DEVELOPER_DIR="$dir"
    fi
fi
```

**Persist for your shell:**

- macOS (zsh, default): append to `~/.zshrc`
- macOS (bash): append to `~/.bash_profile`

**Trap to remember:**

- After upgrading Xcode (e.g. Xcode 15 → 16), run `sudo xcode-select --switch /Applications/Xcode.app/Contents/Developer` to point at the new install.
- If `xcodebuild` reports "tool ... can't be located", check `xcode-select -p` — it might still point at Command Line Tools (`/Library/Developer/CommandLineTools`) instead of full Xcode.
- For multiple Xcode versions, use `xcversion` (rbenv-style switcher) or symlink swapping.

Related: [[cross-platform-bash]] (common Bash-only / never-PowerShell rule).
